diff:1670646396:1670632290:=117,135d116%0a%3c #foxbegin 221210-042636-56270#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Characteristics of different types of aphasia %0a%3c -> - ssbisht%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 20:26-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221210-042636-56270 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I found it interesting how Wernicke's aphasia differs from other types of aphasia. While their speech is fluent, they can't comprehend spoken messages or repeat phrases. An example of a sentence a person with Wernicke's aphasia might say is "You know that smoodle pinkered and that I want to get him round and take care of him like you want before" (https://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/aphasia). It is interesting to see this example because it doesn't look immediately ungrammatical but definitely doesn't follow the Gricean maxims.%0a%3c %0a%3c The other most common type of aphasia is Broca's aphasia, which is similar to Wernicke's aphasia in that a person can't repeat phrases, but someone with Broca's aphasia has non-fluent speech but can typically comprehend others well. This is in contrast to WA because someone with Broca's aphasia recognizes that they aren't saying what they want to, whereas someone with WA might not understand that what they are saying has errors.%0a%3c %0a%3c (https://www.aphasia.org/aphasia-definitions/)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221210-042636-56270#%0a
